There are clear over-densities

00:32:59.623 --> 00:33:02.750
in some places and clear
under-densities in others.

00:33:02.750 --> 00:33:06.759
And it turns out that the
Large-Scale Structure of the

00:33:06.759 --> 00:33:10.920
Universe is sort of like a
bubble, some soap bubbles.

00:33:10.920 --> 00:33:13.903
And so, they've got walls,
and then, there are voids in

00:33:13.903 --> 00:33:17.292
the middle of the walls.
And where those walls connect

00:33:17.292 --> 00:33:20.690
are particularly dense clumps.
Another way you can think about

00:33:20.690 --> 00:33:22.930
it is that there are these kinds
of these filaments,

00:33:22.930 --> 00:33:26.979
things that go through space
where there are unusually large

00:33:26.979 --> 00:33:29.988
numbers of galaxies.
So, the most recent redshift

00:33:29.988 --> 00:33:32.932
survey, which goes out much,
much further than the one I

00:33:32.932 --> 00:33:35.019
just showed you,
that was the first.

00:33:35.019 --> 00:33:37.730
That one sort of goes out to
here.

00:33:37.730 --> 00:33:40.880
But now they've the 2DF,
Two Degree Field.

00:33:40.880 --> 00:33:44.539
This is a telescope that can
look at--measure the redshifts

00:33:44.539 --> 00:33:48.262
of galaxies within two degrees
of each other all at the same

00:33:48.262 --> 00:33:49.520
time.
So, you get many,

00:33:49.520 --> 00:33:51.534
many redshifts.
I think they have close

00:33:51.534 --> 00:33:53.610
to--maybe 100,000 redshifts.
Here.

00:33:53.610 --> 00:33:57.339
Each blue dot is a galaxy.
And you can see the structure.

00:33:57.339 --> 00:34:00.752
You can see the structure
really cleanly with these void

00:34:00.752 --> 00:34:03.943
areas surrounded by walls.
And then, when the walls run

00:34:03.943 --> 00:34:06.227
into each other,
there are particularly dense

00:34:06.227 --> 00:34:08.912
clumps of galaxies.
So, that's the current

00:34:08.912 --> 00:34:13.257
structure of the Universe that
we want our simulation to end up

00:34:13.257 --> 00:34:14.730
looking like.
Yes?

00:34:14.730 --> 00:34:16.663
Student: Why does
