00:37:16.606 --> 00:37:19.250
easier to visualize.
So, let's try that.

00:37:19.250 --> 00:37:23.085
See, it's the same simulation,
except the box is rotating,

00:37:23.085 --> 00:37:26.652
and so, you get a better sense,
I think, of what these

00:37:26.652 --> 00:37:32.239
structures actually look like.
I'll do it once more.

00:37:32.239 --> 00:37:34.823
As they collect into these
filaments and the filaments

00:37:34.823 --> 00:37:37.751
collect together.
And so, what you can do with

00:37:37.751 --> 00:37:41.755
the output of something like
this, with what it is at the

00:37:41.755 --> 00:37:43.900
very end--whoops,
I missed.

00:37:43.900 --> 00:37:47.853
Try it one more time.
Let me see if I can pause

00:37:47.853 --> 00:37:51.815
before it gets--before it
regroups.

00:37:51.815 --> 00:37:54.789
All right.
So, here is a small redshift.

00:37:54.789 --> 00:37:58.822
When you get to this point,
there are mathematical ways of

00:37:58.822 --> 00:38:01.440
saying, you know,
how clumpy is it?

00:38:01.440 --> 00:38:06.138
How stringy is it?
And you can compare the results

00:38:06.138 --> 00:38:11.419
of simulations of this kind with
actual observations from the

00:38:11.419 --> 00:38:15.266
redshift surveys.
And so, in this particular

00:38:15.266 --> 00:38:22.639
case, it worked.
So, let me go back to

00:38:22.639 --> 00:38:33.800
here--yes--oh,
it's down here--whoops.

00:38:33.800 --> 00:38:36.922
There we go.
There, that's where I want to

00:38:36.922 --> 00:38:39.863
be for the moment.
And the consequence of these

00:38:39.863 --> 00:38:42.807
kinds of things is,
it turns out that most,

00:38:42.807 --> 00:38:48.260
as I said before,
mostly what you constrain,

00:38:48.260 --> 00:38:57.139
and so, you compare the
simulations to redshift surveys.

00:38:57.139 --> 00:39:01.720
And the consequence of that is
that you constrain the amount,

00:39:01.720 --> 00:39:05.689
and also, to a lesser extent,
the type, the behavior,

00:39:05.689 --> 00:39:09.059
of dark matter.
Because it's the matter that's

00:39:09.059 --> 00:39:11.275
pulling things together.
And in a way,

00:39:11.275 --> 00:39:13.880
you can think about these
little clumps and filaments.

00:39:13.880 --> 00:39:16.678
That's places where the
Universe has already stopped and

00:39:16.678 --> 00:39:18.332
contracted.
So, it had a little extra

00:39:18.332 --> 00:39:19.648
density.
So, it hit--so,

00:39:19.648 --> 00:39:21.949
it was beyond the critical
density.

00:39:21.949 --> 00:39:25.674
And so, that little piece of
the Universe stopped and turned

00:39:25.674 --> 00:39:29.840
around, even though the Universe
as a whole continues to expand.

00:39:29.840 --> 00:39:34.540
All right, so, now.
What do we have?

00:39:34.540 --> 00:39:40.320
Let's go back to the plot.
There's 1.

00:39:40.320 --> 00:39:44.225
Here's 1.
And so, we have the supernovae

00:39:44.225 --> 00:39:47.599
forcing you to be in this box,
here.

00:39:47.599 --> 00:39:52.436
We have the Cosmic Microwave
Background forcing you to be in

00:39:52.436 --> 00:39:56.176
this box, here.
And now, we're going to have a

00:39:56.176 --> 00:40:00.868
straight vertical line in this
plot, because we know how much

00:40:00.868 --> 00:40:05.170
dark matter there is from the
structure simulations.

00:40:05.170 --> 00:40:06.840
Now, there are two
possibilities.

00:40:06.840 --> 00:40:13.955
Supposing it comes in
here–this is a good answer,

00:40:13.955 --> 00:40:19.789
because then,
everything is consistent.

00:40:19.789 --> 00:40:23.800
Alternatively,
however, it could come in here.

00:40:23.800 --> 00:40:28.266
This would be awkward,
because if it came in there,

00:40:28.266 --> 00:40:33.716
there would be no answer that
would simultaneously satisfy all

00:40:33.716 --> 00:40:37.062
of these constraints.
And so, then,

00:40:37.062 --> 00:40:42.197
something is wrong either with
one of these determinations of

00:40:42.197 --> 00:40:46.989
the cosmic parameters,
or with the theory as a whole.

00:40:46.989 --> 00:40:52.989
Could be either observational
badness or theoretical badness.

00:40:52.989 --> 00:40:57.856
And remember one – you know,
we did assume – in even

00:40:57.856 --> 00:41:01.749
making this plot,
you're assuming that you're

00:41:01.749 --> 00:41:06.969
dealing with a Cosmological
Constant as the form of the dark

00:41:06.969 --> 00:41:09.816
energy.
And, as we discussed last time,

00:41:09.816 --> 00:41:12.882
it's possible that it isn't
constant, that it's something

00:41:12.882 --> 00:41:14.704
else.
And so, if you ended up--if

00:41:14.704 --> 00:41:17.369
these things didn't work,
you'd have to ask yourself,

00:41:17.369 --> 00:41:19.829
do I have any clue how the dark
energy works?

00:41:19.829 --> 00:41:22.233
And the answer would be,
no, and you would kind of have

00:41:22.233 --> 00:41:23.969
to abandon the Cosmological
Constant.

00:41:23.969 --> 00:41:27.710
I think that's the easiest way
out if things don't work,

00:41:27.710 --> 00:41:30.703
because dark matte--we don't
know what it is,

00:41:30.703 --> 00:41:34.401
but we do know what it does.
It exerts gravity and pulls

00:41:34.401 --> 00:41:37.321
things together.
So, no matter what the answer

00:41:37.321 --> 00:41:40.228
to what it is,
its gravity will still be the

00:41:40.228 --> 00:41:42.469
same.
Dark energy--not only do we not

00:41:42.469 --> 00:41:44.881
know what it is,
we don't really know what it

00:41:44.881 --> 00:41:46.427
does,
except that at the moment,

00:41:46.427 --> 00:41:48.429
it's causing a certain amount
of acceleration.

00:41:48.429 --> 00:41:51.892
And so, if you were satisfied
that all the observations were

00:41:51.892 --> 00:41:55.531
right, you might also think that
your simulations have left out

00:41:55.531 --> 00:41:59.230
something important.
That could easily be that you

00:41:59.230 --> 00:42:03.178
don't fully understand how
structure evolves from a

00:42:03.178 --> 00:42:07.271
Z of 3,000 to now.
That's certainly true at some

00:42:07.271 --> 00:42:09.867
level, and so,
there are various ways you

00:42:09.867 --> 00:42:16.299
could get out of it.
But the nice thing about it is

00:42:16.299 --> 00:42:23.604
it's a test of cosmology.
Basically, if you have one

00:42:23.604 --> 00:42:30.466
measurement of two variables,
the variables being the amount

00:42:30.466 --> 00:42:36.050
of dark energy and the amount of
dark matter,

00:42:36.050 --> 00:42:39.092
that doesn't tell you--all that
does is it establishes a

00:42:39.092 --> 00:42:41.360
relationship between the two
variables.

00:42:41.360 --> 00:42:43.650
It doesn't actually measure
either one of them.

00:42:43.650 --> 00:42:46.551
And so, you get some allowed
region like this or this,

00:42:46.551 --> 00:42:48.960
but you don't actually make a
measurement.

00:42:48.960 --> 00:42:54.962
If you have two measurements of
two variable--if you think of it

00:42:54.962 --> 00:43:00.011
in a mathematical sense,
this is two equations and two

00:43:00.011 --> 00:43:02.539
unknowns.
This you can solve.

00:43:02.539 --> 00:43:08.348
So, then, you measure values
for--well, in this case,

00:43:08.348 --> 00:43:13.040
Ω_λ and
Ω_matter.

00:43:13.040 --> 00:43:15.181
And that's nice.
Then, you can,

00:43:15.181 --> 00:43:17.799
you know, quote what the values
are, once you've done this,

00:43:17.799 --> 00:43:20.192
to however--whatever the
precision of your measurement

00:43:20.192 --> 00:43:24.995
turns out to be.
If you have three measurements

00:43:24.995 --> 00:43:30.779
of two variables,
that's a test of the theory,

00:43:30.779 --> 00:43:37.977
because it is not guaranteed
that you'll get a consistent

00:43:37.977 --> 00:43:41.276
result.
In general, if you write down

00:43:41.276 --> 00:43:44.850
three lines in a two-dimensional
space, you don't pick out a

00:43:44.850 --> 00:43:47.699
single point,
because they don't all cross at

00:43:47.699 --> 00:43:49.942
the same place.
And so, if they do,

00:43:49.942 --> 00:43:52.420
then you've got a consistent
result.

00:43:52.420 --> 00:43:55.241
And then, you have tested the
theory because your prediction

00:43:55.241 --> 00:43:57.920
is that all these three lines
cross at the same place.

00:43:57.920 --> 00:44:00.886
They don't have to do that.
So, if you measure something

00:44:00.886 --> 00:44:03.569
and it works out that way,
then you've tested the theory

00:44:03.569 --> 00:44:05.179
and, kind of,
come out on top.

00:44:05.179 --> 00:44:13.789
So, let me end today's class by
showing you the answer.

00:44:13.789 --> 00:44:18.360
This is what we know about the
Universe.

00:44:18.360 --> 00:44:25.969
Let's see, what have I done
with my--oh, there it is.

00:44:25.969 --> 00:44:29.280
This is the allowed region of
the supernovae.

00:44:29.280 --> 00:44:33.266
And what they've done is,
in each of the cases,

00:44:33.266 --> 00:44:37.860
there's a sort of--I think it's
a one sigma region.

00:44:37.860 --> 00:44:41.226
So, there's a 2/3 chance it'll
live inside here,

00:44:41.226 --> 00:44:44.234
and a--;well,
over 90% chance that it lives

00:44:44.234 --> 00:44:48.611
inside the broader area.
So, the supernovae force you to

00:44:48.611 --> 00:44:51.458
be here.
The Cosmic Microwave Background

00:44:51.458 --> 00:44:54.940
is the green result and it
forces you to be here.

00:44:54.940 --> 00:44:57.835
And then, the clusters,
Large-Scale Clustering,

00:44:57.835 --> 00:45:00.290
force you to be here,
and they cross.

00:45:00.290 --> 00:45:04.207
So, this is the big triumph.
You've tested the theory by

00:45:04.207 --> 00:45:08.704
measuring it in three different
ways for two parameters--namely,

00:45:08.704 --> 00:45:12.630
the dark energy density and the
dark matter density.

00:45:12.630 --> 00:45:16.234
Now, there are a couple other
interesting things to note on

00:45:16.234 --> 00:45:17.747
this plot.
One is that,

00:45:17.747 --> 00:45:20.498
in some cases,
the Universe expands forever,

00:45:20.498 --> 00:45:22.929
and in some cases,
it re-collapses.

00:45:22.929 --> 00:45:25.369
And we're well into the
expansion region.

00:45:25.369 --> 00:45:31.530
There's also the question of
the geometry of the Universe.

00:45:31.530 --> 00:45:34.509
The more stuff there is,
either dark energy or dark

00:45:34.509 --> 00:45:37.309
matter, the more curved the
Universe becomes.

00:45:37.309 --> 00:45:40.314
And so, you can ask yourself,
is the Universe curved in such

00:45:40.314 --> 00:45:42.250
a way that it curves back on
itself?

00:45:42.250 --> 00:45:45.195
Is it basically flat,
giving you Euclidian geometry,

00:45:45.195 --> 00:45:48.139
or does it curve backwards and
extend infinitely?

00:45:48.139 --> 00:45:51.019
And that's these three
situations, here.

00:45:51.019 --> 00:45:54.832
If the sum is equal to 1,
then the Universe is flat and

00:45:54.832 --> 00:45:58.199
Euclidian.
And so, that separates these

00:45:58.199 --> 00:46:00.915
two.
Now, as somebody pointed out a

00:46:00.915 --> 00:46:04.012
few classes ago,
if you have too much dark

00:46:04.012 --> 00:46:08.173
energy, then you never cross 0.
And you never have a Big Bang,

00:46:08.173 --> 00:46:11.359
because the acceleration has
been so great that you must have

00:46:11.359 --> 00:46:14.970
started out coming down and been
bent up toward where we are now.

00:46:14.970 --> 00:46:18.170
That's this region up here.
No Big Bang.

00:46:18.170 --> 00:46:21.199
And so, we're well away from
that as well.

00:46:21.199 --> 00:46:27.365
And so, this basically sums up
what we currently know about the

00:46:27.365 --> 00:46:31.411
expansion of the Universe.
That we have a constraint going

00:46:31.411 --> 00:46:33.691
this way, a constraint going
this way, a constraint going

00:46:33.691 --> 00:46:36.095
this way.
And you can see why I say that

00:46:36.095 --> 00:46:39.353
in a kind of philosophical
sense, all three of these

00:46:39.353 --> 00:46:41.780
measurements are equally
important,

00:46:41.780 --> 00:46:45.539
because it's the fact that
you've got three of them that

00:46:45.539 --> 00:46:49.047
allows a test of the theory.
And we've talked a lot about

00:46:49.047 --> 00:46:51.196
the supernovae.
You could talk just as much

00:46:51.196 --> 00:46:53.977
about the Cosmic Microwave
Background or about Large-Scale

00:46:53.977 --> 00:46:55.811
Clustering,
and the comparison of

00:46:55.811 --> 00:46:57.730
simulations with redshift
surveys.

00:46:57.730 --> 00:47:01.033
We obviously aren't going to
